  "title": "Relationism",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "925b107699ccfd0a",
      "text": "The term relationism is used in Pile to indicate a more radical understanding of relations than is found in e.g. ‘relational databases’. Generally speaking, relations are considered to be links or connections between objects (events, things, people etc.) They can be described, characterized and categorized. Traditionally we use a clear distinction between objects and relations. The relationist approach does not make this distinction but integrates object and relation in one, resulting in ‘connective objects’ that have the properties of objects as well as of relations. As relations, they connect other such relations, as objects, they can be individually addressed, referred and interpreted (externally). In the relationist approach, everything can be expressed in terms of relations. ‘Things’ (objects, reality, data etc.) emerge or are generated by navigating the pure relation space (e.g. of language, thought, Pile space…). [https://web.archive.org/web/20081221001445/http://www.pilesys.com/new/faq.php?cat_id=1 archive] "
    }
